---
import ArticleLayout from '../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import Reassurance from '../components/Reassurance.astro';
import MidCta from '../components/MidCta.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/PullQuote.astro';
import FaqSection from '../components/FaqSection.astro';
import CtaBlock from '../components/CtaBlock.astro';
import EnquiryForm from '../components/locked/EnquiryForm.astro';
import RelatedPanel from '../components/RelatedPanel.astro';

const slug = '/seafarer-mortgage-deposit';

const reassuranceLines = [
  'A deposit built up from US dollar or euro pay.',
  'Savings held in an overseas account.',
  'A gifted deposit from close family.',
  'UK resident, or living abroad between contracts.',
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'How much deposit does a seafarer need for a mortgage?',
    a: 'There is no single figure. A UK-resident seafarer can often be considered for the same deposit levels as any UK employee, while a non-resident applicant tends to be asked for a larger deposit and has a shorter list of lenders. The deposit you need depends on your residency, how you are paid and the property, all subject to lender criteria.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I use savings held in a foreign currency as my deposit?',
    a: 'Yes. Foreign currency savings are widely accepted once converted to sterling. A lender will want to see where the money came from and a clear trail through your bank statements, so keep evidence of how the deposit was built up. The currency itself is rarely the obstacle.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can a seafarer use a gifted deposit?',
    a: 'Yes. Many lenders accept a gifted deposit, usually from a close family member, supported by a short letter confirming the money is a gift, is not repayable and gives the giver no stake in the property. A gift from abroad is workable too, though expect extra checks on the source of the funds.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I start?',
    a: 'Use the 60-second check and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers and tell you where you stand. You can also call us on 01202 155992. You must be on UK soil to receive advice.',
  },
];

const relatedCards = [
  { title: 'Mortgages for seafarers', href: '/mortgage-as-a-seafarer', line: 'The full picture for seafarer mortgages.' },
  { title: 'Foreign currency income', href: '/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income', line: 'How lenders convert and discount non-sterling pay.' },
  { title: 'Seafarers Earnings Deduction mortgages', href: '/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage', line: 'Getting a mortgage while you claim the Seafarers Earnings Deduction.' },
  { title: 'Merchant navy mortgages', href: '/merchant-navy-mortgage', line: 'Specialist help for merchant navy pay.' },
  { title: 'Check your eligibility', href: '/check', line: 'Five quick questions, about 60 seconds.' },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="Seafarer Mortgage Deposit: How Much You Need | Mortgage One"
  description="Yes, seafarers can often use standard deposits. How residency, foreign currency savings and gifted deposits affect the loan to value a lender will offer."
  eyebrow="Seafarer mortgage questions"
  heading="How much deposit does a seafarer need for a mortgage?"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { name: 'How much deposit does a seafarer need for a mortgage?', href: slug },
  ]}
  scenario="seafarer"
>
  <p>
    Often no more than any other buyer. A seafarer is not asked for a bigger deposit simply for being a seafarer. The
    figure depends on where you are tax resident, how you are paid and the property itself, not on the job. Get those
    points in front of a lender that understands seafarers and the deposit you need usually sits in the same range as
    anyone else's.
  </p>

  <Reassurance title="Deposits we see regularly" lines={reassuranceLines} />

  <h2>Is there a standard deposit for seafarers?</h2>
  <p>
    There is no single number. A UK-resident seafarer can often be considered for the same deposit levels as any UK
    employee, with a range of residential mortgages available from around a 5% to 10% deposit, which is a loan to value
    (LTV) of 90% to 95%, subject to criteria. Loan to value is simply the size of the mortgage measured against the
    price of the property, so a smaller deposit means a higher LTV. A larger deposit lowers the LTV and tends to widen
    the choice of lenders and rates, but it is not a requirement of being a seafarer.
  </p>

  <h2>How does where you live affect your deposit?</h2>
  <p>
    Residency does more to shape your deposit than your line of work does. A UK-resident seafarer with recent UK address
    history can frequently reach standard deposit levels, in the 90% to 95% LTV band described above and subject to
    criteria. A non-resident applicant, or someone with limited recent UK address history, tends to be asked for a
    larger deposit, often in the region of 25% or more, which is an LTV of 75% or below, and a shorter list of lenders
    will consider the case. The deposit moves with your circumstances, which is why we confirm them before pointing you
    at a lender. The wider picture sits on our <a href="/mortgage-as-a-seafarer">mortgages for seafarers</a> page.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Tell us where you live and how you are paid, and we will tell you where you stand."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <h2>Can you fund the deposit from foreign currency savings?</h2>
  <p>
    Yes. Many seafarers build a deposit from pay held in US dollars, euros or another currency, and that is widely
    accepted once it is converted to sterling. What a lender looks at is not the currency but the source of the funds.
    It wants to see that the money is yours, where it came from and a clear trail through your bank statements. Savings
    accumulated from contracted pay are straightforward to evidence. How that same income is assessed for affordability
    is covered on our <a href="/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income">foreign currency income</a> page.
  </p>

  <h2>Can a seafarer use a gifted deposit?</h2>
  <p>
    Yes. A gifted deposit, usually from a close family member, is accepted by a large part of the market. The lender
    will ask for a short letter from the person making the gift, confirming the money is a gift rather than a loan, is
    not repayable, and leaves them with no stake in the property. A gift from family living abroad is workable too,
    though expect more thorough checks on the source of the funds, which is normal rather than a sign of a problem.
  </p>

  <PullQuote quote="Where your deposit comes from matters to a lender as much as how big it is." />

  <h2>What a lender wants to see about your deposit</h2>
  <p>
    Behind every deposit is a source-of-funds check, and for seafarers it is worth preparing for early. Have evidence of
    how the money was built up, whether that is saved contracted pay, the sale of an asset or a documented gift, and
    keep a clean trail through your statements so an underwriter can follow it rather than guess at it. Deposit and how
    much you can borrow are two sides of the same case, so we look at both together. You must be on UK soil to receive
    advice, so we confirm your circumstances properly before recommending anything.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Not sure your deposit and its source will satisfy a lender? Let us check it for you."
    label="Check Your Options"
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <FaqSection items={faqs} />

  <CtaBlock
    heading="See what your deposit supports"
    line="Tell us how your deposit is made up and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <EnquiryForm scenario="seafarer" />

  <RelatedPanel cards={relatedCards} />

  <p class="risk-warning">
    Think carefully before securing your debts against your home. Your home may be repossessed if you do not keep up
    repayments on your mortgage.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>

<style>
  .risk-warning {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
  }
</style>
